  "why": "The paper enforces semantic consistency and naturalness where applicable. Semantic consistency is enforced by designing mutations in the interpretation space, associating preconditions that must hold on the original interpretation before applying a mutation, and by producing a matching mutated interpretation (i.e., the oracle depends on semantic-preserving, coordinated interpretation changes). Naturalness is enforced by restricting mutation resources to real-world entities from a prior dataset and performing multiple conformity checks (pose/perspective, vanishing-point matching, brightness/lighting similarity, placement on road, size/occlusion filters) before accepting a mutant. The implementation consistently parameterizes image mutations from real sensor data (resources) rather than applying arbitrary pixel-level edits, which preserves realism and avoids the kinds of cumulative drift that arise when mutations are applied only relative to the most recent mutant. While the authors acknowledge remaining limitations (e.g., imperfect shadows, some nonconforming outputs and a discriminator that did not yet succeed), the method nevertheless enforces the semantic and naturalness constraints required by the metric across generated tests.",
  "evidence": "Page 1960, Sec. 3.2 (Semantic Mutations with semSensFuzz): \"Second, we associate a set of preconditions Prec with each mutation δ, specified in terms of the interp that defines whether δ is applicable to a given t. If Prec(interp) is not satisfied, then δ is not applicable to that test.\"; \"Third, we enable the parameterization of δ_r to employ real sensor data to increase the likelihood of conformity. For example, ... δ_addCar_r could put the car from r_j into r_i. In the case of images, we use the entity pose, perspective, lighting, and adjacent entities in the interpretation to define the context.\" Page 1962–1963, Sec. 4.3.1 (Adding an Entity — Implementation): \"we add the constraint that the entity must be placed at the same relative physical coordinates to the camera in the new test case as it was in the source test case... Retaining the same pose increases the likelihood that the added car will appear in the correct perspective in t'.\"; \"we divide the images into quadrants and consider two images to be compatible if their vanishing points are in the same quadrant.\"; \"if the entity does not have a median value within 5 units (~2%) of the median value of the base image target area, then it fails the conformity check.\"; \"to validate this, semImFuzz checks if the lower left corner of the entity’s bounding box is on the road.\" Page 1964, Sec. 4.4.4 (Discriminators for Conformity Checking): \"We explored this approach, training a binary classifier ... The discriminator learned to differentiate between the classes, but could not differentiate conforming versus nonconforming images.\" (acknowledging limits but showing the main approach enforces plausibility checks)."
